00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
So, anyway, into the technical stuff to talk about today.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:36.000
The most exciting thing that you're working on right now is that as an engineering manager for Posit, which formerly known as RStudio, and the makers of RStudio, you're now working there as an engineering manager.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:47.000
And your project that you're leading the development of is something called Positron, which is described as a next-generation IDE, integrated development environment, for data science.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
So that is what RStudio was many years ago.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:04:00.000
I was using RStudio since 2007, that I can kind of at least since then.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:11.000
And it was definitely my go-to IDE when I was primarily an R developer back then, an R data scientist, although I guess I wouldn't have used the word data scientist in 2007.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
Yeah, right? Right? Yeah.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:29.000
And so with Positron, what are the gaps or limitations that you're addressing that aren't covered by things like RStudio, VS Code, or Jupyter Notebooks, which might be the go-to IDEs for data scientists or software developers today?

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:43.000
Yeah, if I was going to sum up the one gap I feel like that Positron is working to address, it's that there isn't something out there right now that can be one place you go to do all your data science.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
So Positron is not a general-purpose IDE.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
It is specifically an IDE built to do data science.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And I come from a science background, and I've always been someone who wrote code for my data analysis, but I've always really felt that my needs were a little different than someone who is writing general-purpose code, like to build a website or to make a mobile app.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Like, people who write code to analyze data are different in some real ways.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:21.000
It's not that it's like they're worse coders or like –

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
No, no, I really do think that.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
It's not. It's not.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Like, I don't think it is that people who write code to analyze data do a worse job writing code.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:34.000
It's that their needs are different and that they're writing code in a different way.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:51.000
So folks who have been – for example, who have been using DS Code as a data science IDE have really felt that tension, where they're like, this is really general-purpose, and instead – and I'm trying to kind of customizing it using extensions to fit my needs.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.000
So Positron is meant to specifically be a data science IDE.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Positron is also like a real driving reason why we've built it the way it is, is that it is a multilingual or polyglot IDE.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:15.000
A lot of the environments you might download to do scientific computing or data science or data analysis are built specifically for one language.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:17.000
So I know all of us have used these.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:21.000
So RStudio is an example of one of these, like MATLAB, Spyder.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:28.000
Like, there's a lot of – there are a lot of, you know, environments in which you would do data analysis that are just built for one language.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:33.000
And increasingly, I just think that's not how many people – that's not how as many people work.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:42.000
Many, many people use multiple languages, whether it's on one project that literally uses multiple languages over the course of a week.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.000
They pick up different projects that use different languages.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:52.000
Or almost certainly on the span of years or your career, you use different languages because things change in our ecosystem.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.000
Like you said, you started with R and, you know, now you use other languages.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:07.000
There are so many people who use combinations of R and Rust, you know, or they work on projects that's like Python plus front-end kind of technologies, JavaScript, you know, HTML, et cetera.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Or like almost any data science language plus SQL, right?

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:22.000
Like, very few people – IDE that is built to use one language, for very few people is that really going to fit all of the needs that they have over the course of a week, a month, or multiple years.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:37.000
So, Positron is built with a design such that the front-end user-facing features are about the tasks you need to do, like whether that is interactively write code, whether that's dealing with your plots,

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:42.000
whether that's seeing, exploring your data, like, you know, in a visual way.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:47.000
And then there are back-end language packs that provide the engines for those front-end features.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:51.000
So, it's – Positron is very early days for Positron.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:55.000
We only made it public about six weeks ago as of the day we're recording this.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.000
So, it is currently shipping with support for Python and R.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:12.000
But it is designed in such a way that other data science languages can be added because there's a separation between the, like, the front-end features and what is driving them.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So, we look forward to adding support for other languages as they, as you know, we collaborate with other data science communities or, like, new things come up, right?

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:27.000
Like, new exciting sort of ways of doing data science come up.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:30.000
So, the Polyglot IDE part to me, that makes a huge amount of sense.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
I get that especially as a contrast to RStudio.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:44.000
For people who are writing code as a data analyst or a data scientist, people who are working with data, what is different that we need specifically relative to another software developer?

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:45.000
Yeah.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:55.000
So, I think one piece that is very different is that the process of writing code is more exploratory, is more interactive.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
And that's not wrong or bad.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:06.000
That is actually just the fact that instead of getting a spec from a product manager and building a product, like, that's not what data scientists, data analysts do.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:16.000
They, you start with data and you often don't know what you can or should do in detail until you start that process.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:26.000
And if you have a code writing process that is more exploratory, you need more supports for writing in that interactive exploratory mode.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:34.000
Some things that support that are things like a, like, truly, truly fully featured interactive console.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
Of course, that does exist in various ways.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.000
Like, people get at that in various ways.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:43.000
Like, when they use notebooks or using, say, a Python REPL.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:54.000
But there are, if you get to a truly fully featured interactive console where what happens in the console is then reflected in the rest of the, where you're working.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:59.000
Like, say, in Positron we have what we call a variables pane.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:06.000
If you come from our studio, you may be familiar with something called, like, an environment pane where you see all the things you've, and it updates, right?

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:07.000
Like, as you change things.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:09.000
Or the plots that you see.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:10.000
You have them all right there.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:11.000
You can scroll through them.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
You can, if you change and make a new plot, you see it pop up there.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.000
And you have that really interactive way of working.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:28.000
Some of the other things that I know really make a difference for people help inside of the IDE where you are working.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:33.000
So you don't, you know, you're working along, you're like, ah, wait, what is the function signature?

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
Or, like, maybe I want to look at the docs for this.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:43.000
So instead of having to get out of a flow state and go somewhere else and re-docs, like, on a website.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:52.000
Like, you can open up help right there and copy paste, like, go right back and forth and stay in that kind of flow state.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:55.000
Another thing is you're building interactive apps.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:04.000
Like, you need a way to have that right there and that it updates as you change your code versus having some sort of build process, going somewhere, looking at a browser.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:12.000
There's really quite a lot that if we put it together, we can make people more productive.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:19.000
You know, the company that I work for, Posit, you know, is a formerly known, the company formerly known as RStudio, you know, like, Posit.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:28.000
Like, we do, it's a really fun place to work as someone who likes thinking about the process that people bring to their tasks.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:33.000
Because I do think, like, we are huge believers in code-first data science.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
Like, not no-code solutions, not GUI-based tool.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
Like, people who do data work should be writing code.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
And at the same time, their needs are different.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:44.000
Like, their needs are different.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:58.000
And so we can, like, pretty much every single thing my company does is, like, deeply informed by this belief or, like, how deeply we know that data practitioners are different and that's good and fine.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:04.000
And we can make them more productive by building tools that are specifically for the kinds of tasks they need to do.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:18.000
