00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:41.000
And thankfully, if you're new to mathematical optimization approaches, Gurobi offers a wealth of resources for data scientists, including hands-on training, comprehensive Jupyter notebook examples, and extensive free online courses.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:49.000
Check out episode number 813 of this podcast to learn more about mathematical optimization and all of these great resources from Gurobi.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.000
That's episode number 813.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.000
Makes a huge amount of sense to me.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:09.000
You also talk about, in addition to these kinds of things that are great in an IDE, that are interactive, that allow us as data scientists, data analysts, doing exploratory data analysis that are super helpful.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:15.000
So the kinds of things you mentioned, like a fully-featured interactive console with updated variable pane.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:16.000
So useful.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:22.000
And something that, for example, for me, is missing from Jupyter notebook, which is what I primarily use today.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:29.000
And, yeah, obviously having plots in a way that you can scroll through them separately from your code, it sounds like.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:34.000
Whereas in my Jupyter notebook, it's all just kind of like one giant stream of information.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:39.000
And then obviously, you know, Jupyter notebooks don't have that kind of built-in help or docs.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:43.000
Although some implementations, like Google Colab, do that.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:50.000
No, there's like an interesting sort of set of overlapping sort of tools in this space.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:55.000
And I do think Positron is existing in somewhere that's different than some of these slightly other places.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:06.000
Like someone maybe who is in a situation where they want a lot – they're like needing a lot of guardrails, right?

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.000
Like often people will start in Jupyter notebooks.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:18.000
But often as you like kind of grow in sophistication, you end up being frustrated by some of those guardrails and constraints.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:21.000
And it's like, well, I need a more fully featured IDE.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
Like I need something.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:30.000
But if I go straight to something like VS Code, it's actually quite challenging to try to get it to be a good fit.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:34.000
I mean, speaking of VS Code, we should say right now.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:45.000
So Positron is now among the list of IDEs that are built on top of the infrastructure that powers VS Code.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:49.000
So there is a repo out there.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
It's called Code OSS.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:59.000
It's open source components that are used to build what you might be familiar with as the Microsoft-branded Visual Studio Code.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:06.000
And there's actually quite a number now of IDEs that are forks of this open source of Code OSS,

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.000
the open source components that are used to build Visual Studio Code.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:17.000
And I think it's actually super interesting because it's like having that as open source has made,

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:22.000
has almost like made it like a commodity, like the building blocks for making an IDE.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:28.000
And it has lowered the bar to people building new IDEs in really interesting ways.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:38.000
Because you can say like, okay, what do I want to experiment with as like a differentiator when it comes to making an IDE?

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:43.000
And one that I bet you and your listeners may have heard of or experimented with is Cursor.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:47.000
Cursor is another fork of this open source code.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:55.000
And it's like it's sort of take on things is that is AI first, like LM coding assistant first.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:00.000
And then like our approach was like data science specific.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:05.000
Like we think people who do data science are different from people who write general purpose code.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
So let's make an IDE just for them.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:15.000
And it means that you can build a new IDE with a smaller team, I think, than you would have in other ways.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:19.000
Because you can concentrate on the things you think are differentiators.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:27.000
And then the pieces that are true for anyone who's writing code, like we all need to save files.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
We all need to look at get merge conflicts, right?

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:34.000
Like you get that by building on top of this infrastructure.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:44.000
The other sort of really interesting piece for building on top of this infrastructure is that you can then make the whole wide,

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:47.000
wide world of VS Code compatible extensions.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
You can make those available to your users.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:17:01.000
So, for example, what this means in our case is people who need a data science specific IDE now have access to that whole world of extension.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:08.000
So if you're like, well, I do data science, but I want to use the Databricks extension or whatever, you know,

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:14.000
like you can end up like getting that extensibility, which has not been true of many of the other kinds.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:22.000
Like if you look at the category of like RStudio, Spyder, you know, like those are quite difficult to extend and customize.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
So it's an interesting choice.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:36.000
And I think it's pretty interesting seeing how we're kind of having this flourishing of IDEs because of the open source nature of the underlying infrastructure for VS Code.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:44.000
Very nice. And yes, so not only do you have CodeOSS as a kind of a backbone that's providing building blocks for Positron

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:48.000
and offering that kind of extensibility through all the VS Code extensions, like you mentioned Databricks there,

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:52.000
any number of extensions that people might want to be able to import.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:56.000
Rainbow tabs, whatever you want, it's out there.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:01.000
In addition to all those things, the Positron project itself is open source.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:09.000
So if people are listening and they want to be contributing, right now at the time of recording, there are 27 people, including I can see your face,

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
as one of those GitHub contributors.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:16.000
Listeners can go and they can contribute to this developing and very exciting project.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:21.000
Yeah, yeah. So Positron is licensed such that it is source available.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:26.000
Anyone can come and look at the source, change it, contribute to it.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:32.000
And it is also licensed such that it is free to use, including for commercial purposes.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:37.000
You can use it, of course, in academia for personal projects, but you can use it at work.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:44.000
It is licensed in such a way that it is free to use in your work as a data scientist.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:48.000
So it's free to get it, so you can read the code.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:55.000
There's real benefit to that kind of model for building and making software.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.000
I'm a big Posit fan.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:03.000
They have sponsored the show in the past, and they may sponsor the show again in the future, so there's that obvious kind of bias.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:08.000
But I feel confident that I would be saying these great things about Posit regardless,

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:17.000
because it's so awesome to have companies like Posit out there that are supporting people like you to be able to be working a huge portion of your time,

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:24.000
I imagine, on open source projects like this, that then anyone can go and contribute to, anyone can go and use.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:31.000
There's already thousands of stars on this GitHub repo, despite only having been released six weeks ago at the time of recording, which is wild.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:34.000
And so, yeah, thanks, Posit, for that kind of system.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:39.000
And, you know, Posit still is a public benefit corporation.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
Yeah, yeah, it's really interesting.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:44.000
So some people hear that, and they're like, what does that mean?

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
It does not mean a nonprofit.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
