01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:56.000
Um, so one of the questions that I, that was brought up in our research by our researcher, Serge Macice,

01:03:56.000 --> 01:04:03.000
that I was really interested in asking you around NLP was that you have pointed out how practitioners, including myself,

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:08.000
tend to use pre-made lists of stop words before they start doing NLP analysis.

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:17.000
So, um, maybe quickly give us your definition of stop words and then tell us why I should stop using a pre-made list.

01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:24.000
So, stop words are, um, are lists of words that people are like, oh, those are not important.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:25.000
I can take them out.

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:29.000
And so they are words like, um, the, and of.

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:35.000
And so, uh, in English, a conservative stop word list would be on the order of like 100.

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:39.000
And a more aggressive stop word list would be on the order of like 1,000.

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:44.000
And the way that these lists were made is that they're, they're old.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:45.000
They're old.

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:48.000
These lists come from like the mid-20th century typically.

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:56.000
They were made by taking huge, for the time, huge corpuses of language and counting up words,

01:04:56.000 --> 01:05:00.000
looking at the top 1,000 and deciding where a cutoff should be.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:05.000
And then deciding, like, a person, a person decided where to make the cutoff.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:10.000
And a person decided, um, are there words that I should or should not keep in.

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:15.000
Um, there are, uh, there are so many problems with stop words.

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:18.000
So, A, some of them literally have typos in them, you know.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:21.000
And if you, you're like, well, is that good or bad?

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:25.000
If someone had a typo for, you know, I don't know.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:27.000
I can't think of a long enough word.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:30.000
But let's say that someone had a typo, like A, D, N.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:32.000
Like, maybe I do want to take that out.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:36.000
But, but it's strange, right, that there are actually, there are some words that have typos in there.

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:44.000
Another thing that happens is that because these were created from list, from, from corpuses of language,

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:52.000
like many books that were put together, you actually end up with evidence of, um, gender bias just in the stop word list.

01:05:52.000 --> 01:05:57.000
Like, because, like, let's say we take a whole huge number of books.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:03.000
Um, there are more uses of those, in those books of he than she.

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:06.000
There are more uses in those books of his than her.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:12.000
And some of those stop word lists actually have, for some of those sets of, you make a list of all the English pronouns.

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:18.000
They have all of them for masculine, and they only have, like, three quarters of them for the feminine version because of where the cutoff was.

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:19.000
Right?

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:25.000
So, you, you're like, oh, man, these are, even though you're like, boy, this is, like, the simplest thing you can do, make a list of words.

01:06:26.000 --> 01:06:37.000
They are, they are, all of our, like, challenges around data analysis, data science, data sources, they show up, even in this, like, dead simplest thing you can do.

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:53.000
So, I, I avoid, now, I now avoid using lists of stop words when I do topic models because, um, they will always end up being, like, the most, um, the most, uh, probable words.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:57.000
But like we just talked about, the most probable words are never very interesting.

01:06:57.000 --> 01:07:04.000
You need to look at these other, these other kind of, um, statistics, give you a better sense of what topics are really about.

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:12.000
When I do supervised, um, machine learning, I often leave them in as well because it turns out it's actually informative.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:19.000
The way some, the documents use even those boring words, it can be predictive.

01:07:19.000 --> 01:07:21.000
Like, they can actually have predictive information.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:25.000
Like, if you're doing classification, how it uses those boring words can help.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:34.000
If I'm doing EDA, I sometimes take them out if I'm, like, trying to show the top, like, most common words and I just, like, well, let me take out, like, those boring words.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:36.000
I do sometimes still take them out there.

01:07:36.000 --> 01:07:48.000
But I often will supplement it with, um, even EDA approaches that provide, uh, ways for seeing differences across groups that do not depend on taking out those stop words.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:53.000
So, some examples of that are looking for log odds of words.

01:07:53.000 --> 01:07:55.000
Like, what are the highest log odds words?

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:59.000
I have a package for this that's called tidy low for tidy log odds.

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:02.000
Or, um, and that's actually an interesting approach.

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:07.000
Anytime you're looking at differences of counts across groups, it doesn't have to be language.

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:10.000
But it's, it's, um, applying it to language is really great.

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:17.000
Um, I still use things like PFIDF as an exploratory tool, uh, which I bet many people have heard of.

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:21.000
And, um, I've written about, like, what it means and people can dig into that more.

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:22.000
So, so that's my pitch.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:23.000
That's my pitch.

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:33.000
My pitch is, um, they suffer from the same problems that almost any data science process suffers from, even though they are so simple.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:39.000
And if you're doing unsupervised smart learning machine, or supervised machine learning, you probably want those words.

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:43.000
And if you're doing EDA, there are alternative approaches that give you better answers.

